    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>User intent</strong> (also called search intent) is the underlying goal a person has when typing a query into a search engine. Google's primary job is matching results to intent — so content that satisfies the correct intent type, format, and depth for a keyword ranks higher and stays ranked longer than content that merely contains the target phrase. Intent is the "why" behind the keyword.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Search Intent, Query Intent</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">You can have the best-optimised meta tags, the fastest page speed, and the most authoritative domain — and still rank on page 3 because your content format doesn't match what searchers actually want.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is user intent?</h2>
        <p>User intent describes the job a search query is trying to accomplish. People searching for "how to bake bread" want instructions, not a bread shop. People searching for "best bread machine 2026" want a comparison and recommendation. People searching for "KitchenAid bread machine buy" want a product page where they can convert.</p>
        <p>Google's machine learning systems — particularly RankBrain (2015) and BERT (2019) — were specifically designed to understand the intent behind queries, not just the literal words. A query like "apple support" has clear navigational intent; a query like "why does my MacBook overheat" has informational intent. Google serves different result types for each.</p>
        <p>Satisfying intent well is what separates a page that ranks briefly from one that ranks permanently. Google's helpful content system explicitly rewards content that "demonstrates first-hand expertise and depth of knowledge" in a way that satisfies the searcher — which is a direct measure of intent alignment.</p>

        <h2 id="four-types">The four types of user intent</h2>
        <p>The standard framework divides search intent into four categories. Understanding which category your target keyword falls into tells you what content format to create.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Intent type</th><th>What the user wants</th><th>Example queries</th><th>Content format</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Informational</strong></td><td>Learn something</td><td>"how does SEO work", "what is a meta description"</td><td>Blog post, guide, explainer, video</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Navigational</strong></td><td>Reach a specific site or page</td><td>"Google Search Console login", "Ahrefs site explorer"</td><td>Homepage, login page, feature page</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Commercial</strong></td><td>Research before buying</td><td>"best SEO tools 2026", "Semrush vs Ahrefs"</td><td>Comparison, roundup, review</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Transactional</strong></td><td>Take an action (buy, sign up, download)</td><td>"buy Ahrefs subscription", "free keyword tool"</td><td>Product page, pricing page, free trial landing page</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Some SEOs use a simpler three-way split: Do (transactional), Know (informational), Go (navigational). Google's own Quality Rater Guidelines use this framework plus "Local" for queries with geographic intent.</p>

        <h2 id="identify-intent">How to identify user intent for any keyword</h2>
        <p>The most reliable intent signal is what Google already ranks — the SERP itself. If you search your target keyword and see ten blog posts in the results, Google has determined searchers want long-form educational content. If you see product pages, create a product page.</p>
        <p>Look at three dimensions when analysing the SERP:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Dominant content type.</strong> Are the results mostly blog posts? Comparison pages? Tool landing pages? Videos? The modal content type tells you the format to match.</li>
          <li><strong>Content angle.</strong> What angle do the top results take? "For beginners" vs "advanced guide" vs "quick checklist" represent different angles for the same broad topic. Match the angle your audience wants.</li>
          <li><strong>Content depth.</strong> Are the top results 500-word explainers or 4,000-word comprehensive guides? Depth signals how thoroughly the topic needs to be covered to satisfy intent.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The SERP is the ground truth</div>
          <p>Keyword tools label intents based on algorithms, but Google's actual rankings are the real answer. For any keyword you care about, Google has already decided what satisfies intent better than any tool can predict. <strong>Study the top 5 results before writing anything.</strong></p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="intent-seo">Why intent alignment is the core SEO ranking factor</h2>
        <p>Keyword density, backlinks, and technical SEO are all ranking factors. But none of them compensate for a fundamental intent mismatch. Here's why:</p>
        <p>When a user clicks your page and immediately returns to the SERP (pogo-sticking), it signals to Google that your content didn't satisfy the query. Over thousands of sessions, this engagement data shifts Google's confidence in your page's relevance. Rankings erode.</p>
        <p>Conversely, a page that keeps users on-site, earns their engagement, and generates low pogo-sticking rates accumulates positive signals. Rankings improve and stabilise — even without additional link building.</p>
        <p>Google confirmed in its 2024 antitrust trial documents that user engagement data (including click data from Chrome) is used in ranking. Intent alignment is the primary driver of that engagement.</p>

        <h2 id="mixed-intent">Mixed intent keywords — the edge case</h2>
        <p>Not every keyword has a single dominant intent. Some queries sit at the intersection of multiple intent types. Examples:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>"project management software"</strong> — some users are researching, others are ready to buy. Google typically shows a mix of comparison posts and product landing pages.</li>
          <li><strong>"SEO audit"</strong> — some want a definition, some want a checklist, some want a tool. The SERP shows a mix of tools, guides, and service pages.</li>
          <li><strong>"protein powder"</strong> — educational content about protein and product pages both appear. Intent is split between learning and buying.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For mixed intent keywords, look at the balance on the SERP and decide which segment to target. A hybrid page that attempts to serve all segments rarely serves any of them well enough to rank strongly.</p>

        <h2 id="intent-content-mapping">Mapping intent to your content strategy</h2>
        <p>Intent alignment should drive content prioritisation, not just individual page decisions. A content strategy built on intent mapping:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Captures informational queries at the top of the funnel (blog posts, guides, glossary terms)</li>
          <li>Captures commercial queries in the middle (comparison pages, alternative pages, best-of roundups)</li>
          <li>Captures transactional queries at conversion (pricing pages, free trial pages, product demos)</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Each stage requires a different content format, a different CTA, and a different measurement approach. A glossary term captures top-of-funnel awareness; a comparison page captures mid-funnel evaluation; a pricing page captures bottom-of-funnel conversion. All three are necessary for a complete organic acquisition strategy.</p>

        <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common intent mistakes that kill rankings</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Writing an informational post for a transactional keyword.</strong> If someone searches "buy X" and you give them a 2,000-word guide, they'll bounce immediately and find a product page elsewhere.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating a product page for an informational keyword.</strong> "How to do keyword research" is not served by a landing page for your keyword tool. Users want a guide.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the content angle.</strong> If all top results are "for beginners" guides and you write an advanced deep-dive, you'll struggle — even if your content is technically superior.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-optimising for keyword volume without checking intent.</strong> A 10,000-searches/month keyword with commercial intent cannot be captured by an informational blog post, regardless of how well-optimised it is.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming intent doesn't change.</strong> Intent for a keyword can shift as a market matures. "AI content writing" three years ago had mostly informational intent; today it has strong commercial and transactional intent. Periodically re-check the SERP for important keywords.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Intent can shift with algorithm updates</div>
          <p>Google's understanding of intent evolves with each core update. A keyword that triggered informational results in 2023 might trigger product pages in 2026 as user behaviour shifts. Monitor your target keywords' SERPs quarterly and update content format if Google's interpretation has changed.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for intent-aligned content</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Search your keyword before writing anything.</strong> Let the SERP tell you what format, depth, and angle to use.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the dominant content format exactly.</strong> If the SERP shows listicles, write a listicle. If it shows tools, consider building a free tool.</li>
          <li><strong>Satisfy the sub-intent too.</strong> Most queries have a primary intent and secondary sub-intents. A "how to do keyword research" guide primarily needs to teach the process — but readers also want tool recommendations. Cover both.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure engagement, not just rankings.</strong> Track average engagement time, scroll depth, and conversion rate as proxies for intent satisfaction. A page ranking #3 with excellent engagement is more durable than a page ranking #1 with poor engagement.</li>
          <li><strong>Update content when the SERP shifts.</strong> If your page's format diverges from new dominant results after an algorithm update, update the format — not just the information.</li>
        </ol>

